---
import OdeLayout from '../../../layouts/OdeLayout.astro';
import Section from '../../../components/ode/Section.astro';
import DataTag from '../../../components/ode/DataTag.astro';
import StatCard from '../../../components/ode/StatCard.astro';
import { odeMeta, odeRoutes } from '../../../i18n/ode';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const m = odeMeta[lang].ricerca;
const r = odeRoutes[lang];

const questions = [
  {
    t: 'Does provenance improve stability prediction?',
    d: 'The cardinal question: do provenance variables (diet, season, rendering, batch history) measurably improve oxidative-stability prediction over the spectrum alone? This is the hypothesis that underpins OdE’s causal datum, and it must be falsified, not assumed.',
  },
  {
    t: 'How do you learn in the low-data regime?',
    d: 'Traced batches are few and costly to characterise. Which strategies (self-supervised pre-training, few-shot, chemistry-informed regularisation) hold when labels are in the tens, not the thousands?',
  },
  {
    t: 'How do you build a causal supply-chain dataset?',
    d: 'The dataset is not collected, it is cultivated inside a certified chain. Which provenance metadata are genuinely informative, how do you pair spectrum and measured outcome, and how do you keep biological covariance between variables under control?',
  },
];

const partner = [
  { k: 'Spectroscopy and chemometrics', d: 'Expertise in NIR and Raman on fatty matrices, signal preprocessing, PLS and PLS-DA models, decomposition of overlapping components.' },
  { k: 'Collaboration model', d: 'Master’s and PhD theses, co-supervision, access to traced samples and to a real industrial use case. Method publication agreed, confidentiality on the supply-chain data.' },
  { k: 'Co-funding and grants', d: 'Jointly building proposals for research calls (regional, national, European) where the meeting of circular bioeconomy, AI and PDO traceability is a fundable theme.' },
];
---
<OdeLayout title={m.title} description={m.description} lang={lang} active="ricerca">
  <header class="hero">
    <p class="ode-eyebrow">Research</p>
    <h1>A door for those who do research</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      This page is an invitation, addressed as a peer to research groups in spectroscopy, chemometrics and
      lipid science. OdE is not after a showcase, it is after interlocutors for the questions it still has
      open. The value is not ours alone: a causal datum linking the traced provenance of the Parmigiano
      Reggiano supply chains to fat stability is a good for the whole territorial ecosystem and for the
      circular bioeconomy, not for a single company.
    </p>
  </header>

  <Section n="1" title="The open research questions">
    <p>
      We state them plainly, including the ones that may not have the answer we hope for. It is the honest
      way to open a scientific dialogue.
    </p>
    <div class="cards">
      {questions.map((q) => (
        <article class="q">
          <h3>{q.t}</h3>
          <p>{q.d}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section n="2" title="The method">
    <p>
      The approach is disciplined and baseline-first: mature chemometrics comes first, advanced models
      enter only where they add measured value. Four choices form its backbone.
    </p>
    <div class="method">
      <article class="mi">
        <span class="mi-k">Data Ladder</span>
        <p>Data capital grows in steps of increasing defensibility: public foundations, real external data,
        a proprietary dataset of traced batches, and finally the flywheel of real batches. The subset that
        matters is the one with provenance, spectrum and outcome paired.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="mi">
        <span class="mi-k">Conformal prediction</span>
        <p>Every prediction comes with a guaranteed-coverage interval and an out-of-distribution gate that
        triggers escalation to the accredited test. Uncertainty is validated, not asserted in words.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="mi">
        <span class="mi-k">Interpretable models</span>
        <p>The chemical explanation matters as much as the prediction: relevant spectral regions,
        consistency with known chemistry (double bonds, aldehydes, peroxides). A model that cannot be read
        is of no use to an assessor.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="mi">
        <span class="mi-k">Lipid foundation model</span>
        <p>Self-supervised pre-training on the unannotated spectral corpus yields a rich encoder; downstream
        tasks fine-tune with few labels. It is the lever against the low-data regime.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
    <p class="note">
      <DataTag kind="fonte" label="Foundation/generalist model per spettroscopia vibrazionale, frontiera 2025-2026" />
      The method is public and shareable; what stays proprietary is the pre-training corpus and the causal
      supply-chain datum. The technical deep dive lives in <a href={r.amsaTecnica}>Under AMSA’s hood</a>.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section n="3" title="The decisive, pre-registered experiment">
    <p>
      The central thesis is not defended in words, it is put to the test before scaling. So we reduced it
      to a single pre-registered experiment, with the success criterion declared before looking at the
      data, to avoid convenient confirmations.
    </p>
    <div class="gate">
      <p class="gate-q">Does provenance measurably improve stability prediction (induction time, OSI) over
      the spectrum alone?</p>
      <ul class="gate-proto">
        <li>About 30 to 40 tallow batches with complete provenance metadata <DataTag kind="stima" label="Plan sample size" />.</li>
        <li>Spectral acquisition and OSI (induction time) measurement on the Rancimat as ground truth.</li>
        <li>Pre-registered comparison between a spectrum-only model and a spectrum-plus-provenance model, RMSE on predicted induction time as the metric.</li>
        <li>Success criterion fixed and deposited before the analysis.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="gate-state">
        <DataTag kind="stima" label="Plan experiment, not yet run" />
        Status: in progress. The protocol is defined, the collection of provenance-paired batches is
        under way. The outcome, either way, is itself the scientific result.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section n="4" title="What we look for in a partner group">
    <div class="cards">
      {partner.map((p) => (
        <article class="q">
          <h3>{p.k}</h3>
          <p>{p.d}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section n="5" title="Honesty about the limits">
    <p>
      Calibrating expectations is part of the method. Using the same tags as across the whole site, we
      distinguish what is demonstrated, what is in progress and what remains a bet.
    </p>
    <div class="stats">
      <StatCard value="Demonstrated" caption="Lipid chemometrics is mature: composition and unsaturation proxies read well from spectra, in line with the literature." kind="fonte" source="NIR/Raman fatty-acid literature" />
      <StatCard value="In progress" caption="The causal provenance-to-stability link: plausible and foundational, but to be validated with the pre-registered experiment." kind="stima" source="OdE plan hypothesis, to be validated" />
      <StatCard value="A bet" caption="Absolute shelf-life prediction is an emergent capability, conditioned by exogenous factors (storage, packaging, light) the spectrum does not capture. Not a fact." kind="bench" />
    </div>
    <div class="caveat">
      <span class="caveat-k">Calibrated expectation</span>
      <p>Oxidation rate also depends on conditions the spectrum does not see. Provenance reduces part of it
      upstream, the measured outcome calibrates it downstream, and every predicted stability stays tied to
      its confidence interval. Absolute shelf-life is to be treated as a research goal, not an acquired
      performance.</p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section n="6" title="Let’s open a dialogue">
    <p>
      If these questions intersect your work, write to us: a thesis, a joint experiment, a grant proposal
      or simply an exchange on method.
    </p>
    <p class="contact">
      <a href="mailto:martignoni.matteo@gmail.com?subject=OdE%20research%20collaboration">martignoni.matteo@gmail.com</a>
    </p>
    <p class="note">
      For the applied and market picture, see <a href={r.amsa}>the technology (AMSA)</a> and the
      <a href={r.visione}>development vision</a>.
    </p>
  </Section>
</OdeLayout>

<style>
  .hero { max-width: 46rem; padding: 0.5rem 0 1rem; }
  .hero h1 { font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3rem); margin: 0.4rem 0 1rem; }
  .lede { font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--body); }
  .note { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.5; max-width: 44rem; }
  .note a { color: var(--accent); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }

  .cards { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(16rem, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; }
  .q { background: var(--panel); border: 1px solid var(--rule); border-radius: var(--ode-radius); padding: 1.1rem 1.2rem; }
  .q h3 { font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 500; color: var(--ink); margin: 0 0 0.4rem; }
  .q p { margin: 0; font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--body); }

  .method { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(16rem, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; margin: 0.4rem 0 1rem; }
  .mi { border-left: 3px solid var(--green-border); padding: 0.2rem 0 0.2rem 1rem; }
  .mi-k { font-family: var(--ode-font-mono); font-size: 0.78rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.04em; color: var(--accent); }
  .mi p { margin: 0.4rem 0 0; font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--body); }

  .gate { background: var(--panel); border: 1px solid var(--rule); border-radius: var(--ode-radius); padding: 1.2rem 1.4rem; margin: 1.2rem 0; }
  .gate-q { font-size: 1.05rem; color: var(--ink); font-weight: 500; margin: 0 0 0.8rem; line-height: 1.4; }
  .gate-proto { padding-left: 1.2rem; margin: 0 0 1rem; line-height: 1.6; }
  .gate-proto li { margin-bottom: 0.35rem; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--body); }
  .gate-proto li::marker { color: var(--accent); }
  .gate-state { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--body); line-height: 1.55; margin: 0; }
  .gate-state .ode-tag { margin-right: 0.3rem; }

  .stats { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(14rem, 1fr)); gap: 0.8rem; margin: 1rem 0; }

  .caveat {
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.34);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--green-border);
    border-radius: 0 var(--ode-radius) var(--ode-radius) 0;
    padding: 0.8rem 1rem; margin: 1rem 0 0; max-width: 44rem;
  }
  .caveat-k { display: block; font-family: var(--ode-font-mono); font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.04em; color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 0.3rem; }
  .caveat p { margin: 0; font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.55; color: var(--body); }

  .contact { font-size: 1.05rem; }
  .contact a { color: var(--accent); font-family: var(--ode-font-mono); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 3px; }
</style>
